This article was written by Huang Ziyi, Wang Zihui, and Li Xiuli

The power of the nation

For almost everyone who rides to Wuhan, the call to arms comes with great urgency.

On the evening of Jan. 22, Zheng Xia, deputy director of the intensive-care unit at the COVID-19, watched with anxiety as the city's pneumonia was confirmed and the number of severe cases was rising. She told the leadership, willing to go to Wuhan support, "there must be a lot of seriously ill doctors. ". At 11:00 am on the 23rd, an hour after Wuhan was shut down, she received a call from the National Health Commission: "because of the current epidemic emergency, you need to go to Wuhan immediately to support, must arrive tonight. "

Zheng Xia immediately packed up her things and took the high-speed train from Hangzhou at 4 pm. She arrived in a city around Wuhan at 8 pm and was sent directly to Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. Zheng Xia told this newspaper that it takes only three or four hours to prepare from the time the mission is received to the time of departure. 24 hours after the request, she was on the front lines of the outbreak from Hangzhou.

Zheng Xia was one of the first medical personnel to support Wuhan. At about the same time, she arrived in Wuhan, as well as from Shanghai, Guangzhou, Beijing and other places in the core of the critical medical disciplines, to treat the gold and Silver Pool Hospital for the treatment of new severe pneumonia patients. Their arrival was the beginning of a nationwide effort to help Wuhan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 14, medical staff in the buffer zone of the isolation ward of Gyeongtan hospital called colleagues. Expedition photography

A day later, Shanghai, Guangdong, the Army Medical University, and five other first full-scale medical teams arrived in Wuhan, Sichuan, Zhejiang, Jiangsu and other teams followed. On the third day of the city closure in Wuhan, there were 14 teams and 1,230 medical personnel travelling thousands of miles to help. Wuhan's fight against the disease became the biggest nationwide support operation after the 2008 Wenchuan County earthquake, with a massive influx of troops and a brief respite for exhausted first-line medical staff.

In February, the national relief operation to the peak, from 29 regions of the country's medical personnel, with a very fast march speed, the support will be extended to the entire Hubei Province. Chartered flights and high-speed trains to Wuhan, in Winter Walking non-stop, the fire line accelerated, only February 8-14, transported 13,000 rescue medical personnel.

Wang Hesheng, deputy director of the National Health Commission and a member of the Standing Committee of the Hubei Provincial Committee, said that as of February 14, a total of 217 medical teams had been dispatched across the country, with 25,633 medical team members supporting Hubei, including 181 teams in Wuhan and 20,374 team members, and that doesn't include the military medical team. "these are far outpacing the scale and pace of 2008 Sichuan earthquake medical aid transfers in 2008. "

"The departure was all very urgent. It basically means after you call us, you have to leave that night or early the next morning, and the preparation time is very short,"Mo Rui, a doctor at a Beijing No. 3 hospital who came to Wuhan to support the National Emergency Medical Rescue Team, told the Financial Times on February 4, they arrived in Wuhan that day, to take over the shelter hospital has not even been built, but all medical teams are on standby. Hospitals and patients have not yet been in place, to come to the rescue of the medical team has arrived first.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A tired nurse rests her eyes against a wall in the severe isolation ward of Wuhan Red Cross Hospital on Feb. 17. Expedition Photograph

Behind the whole country gallops the aid, is Wuhan since the beginning of February to start "should receive receives" the attack fortified combat. General Chen Yixin, secretary general of the Central Political and Legal Affairs Commission, serves as deputy head of the Central Guidance Group, and Wang Hesheng, deputy director of the National Health and Construction Commission, serves as a member of the Hubei Provincial Standing Committee. The Central Guidance Group issued the order of "collecting all the information that should be collected without delay" , "Four categories of people" (confirmed patients, suspected patients, fever patients who can not rule out infection, close contacts of confirmed patients) were required to be classified and centralized treated and quarantined in Wuhan, and 15 shelter hospitals were started one after another, more than 3,000 communities and villages in Wuhan have been mobilized to go door-to-door. Wuhan from "sealed off the city" , towards the "lock people.

At the same time, the notoriously cumbersome diagnostic criteria were lowered, and suspected patients with imaging features of pneumonia were included in the list of clinically diagnosed cases. The release of a large number of patients sent the number of new cases soaring to 14,840 in Hubei Province on February 12, of which 13,332 were clinically diagnosed. Previously unknown unknown to the bottom of the epidemic, for the first time directly and clearly in front of the public.

"Now the attitude of the country in the fight against the epidemic has been very clear. That is to mobilize all kinds of resources. It is most critical that all people form a joint effort to do this, " Chen Erzhen, the leader of the second group of Hubei Medical Team from Shanghai and deputy director of Ruijin Hospital, told the Financial Times, at present, Wuhan has too many patients, its own resources have been difficult to cope with the battle, only with the strength of the country, to fight a victory. Wuhan anti-epidemic, is also a popular anti-epidemic.

Yang Gonghuan, a former deputy director of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, told the Financial Times that if the city closure was considered the first node in the fight against the epidemic, then "it is now entering the second key node. ". In the first node, the epidemic situation is still spreading, the situation is becoming more and more serious, we must adjust the strategy, strengthen the rescue efforts, cure the patients, increase the prevention and control efforts.

Never before in history has there been a showdown... between a single nation and a super-epidemic. And Right now, this is the moment of truth. "It can be said that when the situation is most tight, it is a state of stalemate and confrontation, " said Liang Wannian, the head of the Expert Group on the handling of the epidemic situation under the National Health Commission.

In the heat of battle, the Central Guidance Group issued an order on February 14: Launch a full scale general offensive to defend Hubei and Battle of Wuhan. "Hubei and Wuhan are the decisive places for the whole country to win the battle to prevent and control the epidemic. If Wuhan Wins, Hubei Wins; if Hubei Wins, the whole country wins. "

A serious attack

"Now is the decisive moment, not the decisive moment. " Chen Erzhen believes that from decisive battle to decisive victory, the key lies in adhering to the principle of centralized classification, "centralized patients, centralized experts, centralized resources and centralized treatment. ". He led the team to support Wuhan's Third Hospital Guanggu Hospital district, mainly responsible for the treatment of critically ill patients.

Wuhan, the epicenter of the outbreak, has attracted attention not only for its more than 30,000 confirmed cases, but also for its severe illness and fatality rates, which are significantly higher than in other parts of the country. As of February 15, there were 8,530 severe cases in Wuhan, accounting for 24.2% of the confirmed cases (35,314 cases) , and the case fatality rate was 2.96% , higher than that in Hubei and the whole country.

Jiao Yahui, deputy director of the medical and Health Administration Bureau of the National Health Commission, explained to the public that this was because at first there were only 3 designated hospitals for serious patients in Wuhan, with a total of more than 110 beds, which was seriously inadequate. A large number of seriously ill patients are scattered in more than 20 medical institutions, which is not conducive to management, let alone by a professional medical team in the Department of critical care medicine to treat them, "To a certain extent, this has diluted the strength of high-quality medical resources, but also lead to severe cases with a higher mortality rate factors. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At the end of January, the emergency center of Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University received new severe cases of coronary pneumonia. Photo by Cai Xiaochuan

It is hard to imagine that Wuhan, struggling with the epidemic, is one of the richest regions in the country in terms of medical resources per capita. According to official statistics, Wuhan has 27 top-tier hospitals, ranking sixth in the country in the number of top-tier hospitals per million people (2.44) . At the same time, there are many colleges and universities in Wuhan, with more high-quality medical resources per capita.

But in the health care system, intensive-care unit are a scarce resource. The Wuhan Union Hospital, for example, has only 55 ICU beds, according to its website. A doctor at the West Hospital of Union Medical College said on Weibo that there was no ICU in the hospital area at the beginning of the epidemic, but many patients with serious illness were admitted. Later, 20 ICU beds were opened and soon filled up. Every day, 10 to 20 patients were critically ill but could not be transferred to the ICU. Some patients left while waiting, which was a great blow to the medical staff.

Jiao Yahui revealed that the epidemic in Wuhan lasted for a long time, many cases had not received timely treatment before, severe cases from the onset of illness to the average of 9.84 days in hospital, missed the best opportunity, in the waiting process from mild to severe.

To this end, the National Health Commission on February 4 stressed that the seriously ill patients to "centralized treatment" , medical resources and experts. In addition to the three designated hospitals, the Wuhan Union Hospital, the Tongji Hospital and the East Hospital of the People's Hospital of Wuhan University are newly opened, with a plan to treat 1,000 critically ill patients, the wards are being taken over by an elite intensive-care unit drawn from all over the country. As of February 17, of the 32,000 field support personnel dispatched to Hubei from 29 regions, 11,000 were doctors and nurses in the critical care specialty, close to 10 percent of the national critical care medical personnel resources.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A patient is treated in the isolation ward of Caidian District People's Hospital in Wuhan February 6,2010. Expedition photography

On February 3, the day before the decision was made to focus on the treatment of critically ill patients, Zheng Xia, as the first group of critically ill experts to arrive in Wuhan, attended an emergency meeting of the National Health and Construction Commission. After the meeting, she and several other critical care experts were sent to designated hospitals in Wuhan to assess critically ill patients in need of transportation. Zheng Xia visited eight hospitals in Huangpi district and Qingshan District, Wuhan and saw that there were "very many seriously ill patients" and many patients could not be admitted at all.

"All the doctors are in a hurry, " Ms. Zheng told the Financial Times. Many designated hospitals do not have the necessary rescue conditions, because on weekdays these hospitals do not have many critically ill patients who need oxygen therapy and breathing machines, but had to admit a lot of patients in the emergency period. Because of the conditions, these patients were delayed, backlog in the hospital, outside the hospital there are a large number of patients can not be brought in, at home, "so the pressure of these hospitals is very big. ".

The backlog of critically ill patients is also related to the difficulty of treatment. "The condition is very unpredictable and sometimes it deteriorates rapidly, " Zheng said, adding that the new coronavirus is cunning and can suddenly deteriorate rapidly after a period of relative stability. For example, a patient who seems to be stable in the morning may be in a sudden high fever or even respiratory distress in the evening, the need for pure oxygen on the machine support, or even invasive tracheal intubation, "handling is really very difficult. ".

This is very different from Zheng Xia's participation in the rescue of severe cases of bird flu. "We have a high treatment rate for 'swine flu' In our hospital, and we found that as long as his lungs are supported by ECMO (artificial lung) , many patients are slowly being fed, and when lung function is restored, they can survive step by step, " said Zheng Xia, the rate and degree of deterioration of the disease is far greater than the influenza a period. Chen Erzhen, who helped treat severe cases of SARS, said the overall case fatality rate of new coronavirus pneumonia was lower than that of SARS, but patients with severe cases not only had severe lung damage, but also spread to other organs, causing multiple Organ Dysfunction Syndrome in the body.

In this case, the critical care specialist's main job in the ICU is to do everything possible to keep the patient breathing, reduce other organ damage, and win a window of time for the patient's own immune system to recover. These methods include oxygen therapy, Nasal high-flow oxygen therapy, non-invasive mechanical ventilation, invasive mechanical ventilation, Ecmo and other functional support. "there is no specific medicine yet, " Ms. Zheng stressed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
February 13, the Golden Pool Hospital isolation ward busy medical staff. Expedition photography

For intensive care, medical equipment and resources are weapons, just like soldiers on the battlefield, without machine guns and ammunition. Oxygen is a must, but many field teams in Wuhan have encountered oxygen supply and equipment problems. The later arrival of the chi-aid forces, have strengthened the preparation in this regard, brought the breathing machine, oxygen machine, ECMO and other equipment.

However, not all critically ill patients are able to be transferred to the newly opened intensive care unit as desired. Ms. Cheng said the screening assessment at the time focused only on confirmed patients and also considered the risk of transfer. "screening is mainly for patients who are already in critical condition but can be transferred, " Zheng said, adding that the transfer of critical patients is at high risk and not included in the transfer. So critical care, the sooner the better, to prevent the disease from serious deterioration to critical.

"early treatment is critical, otherwise the disease progresses, " Chen said, emphasizing "early" treatment, which is not only reflected in the treatment of severe cases, but also related to the whole process of fighting the disease. Because critical care requires a large number of personnel and resources, the front line must be moved forward to establish an early identification and early warning system for the progression of common patients to critical care to ensure effective intervention, at the same time in the prevention and control should also be "early detection, early isolation, early treatment. ".

Front line moving forward

However, Wuhan has missed the "early" time point, at the beginning of the epidemic, after the closure of the city. Yang Gonghuan said that the current "due diligence" actually represents the failure of the strategy adopted in the early days after the city's closure. The source of infection has not been controlled, and the area was even in a "very disorderly state. ".

There are three main strategies in the prevention and treatment of infectious diseases: to Find and control the source of infection, to cut off the route of transmission, and to treat patients. If Wuhan anti-epidemic as a battlefield, then the focus on the treatment of critically ill patients is more like the concentration of troops digging trenches, building a fort, is on the defensive. If we want to destroy the enemy and win the victory, we need to take the initiative to attack as if it is urgent to control the source of infection and cut off the route of transmission.

In Wuhan before and after the city closure, seven small and medium-sized hospitals were initially designated as hospitals with insufficient beds. After the implementation of grading diagnosis and treatment, admission channels were sunk into the community, and medical treatment was reported through layers, and a large number of patients were detained at home isolated. On Feb. 1, Wang Chen, an expert in Chinese Academy of Engineering and Critical Care Medicine, visited Wuhan and found that the situation was serious. The capacity of the previously designated hospitals was limited, and a large number of patients could not be admitted and became a source of mobile infection. Wang said this was the "most important factor" that exacerbated the epidemic and was a big pressure on him at the time.

In this case, the Shelter Hospital was proposed to admit a larger number of patients with mild illness. The shelter hospital is a kind of "moving Noah's Ark" , which can solve the problem of insufficient beds by using the large-scale public places in Wuhan and arranging the simple beds, although the conditions are not perfect. "This is not the 'best solution' , but it is the right one and the realistic one, " Wang said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medics wear protective clothing before entering the cabin on February 13. | Hwang woo-suk

"The most important function of the shelter is actually isolation, " said Mo Rui, a doctor with the National Emergency Medical Rescue Team who works at the 1,500-bed Living Room Shelter Hospital in Wuhan. He said the shelter hospital admitted patients with very mild symptoms, internal conditions are limited, unable to do complex tests and treatment, "not even infusion. ". As a doctor, he can only prescribe some oral medicine, more importantly is to monitor and observe the patient's vital signs, "a little bit heavier on the move" to ensure that patients in the shelter "zero deaths.

Mo Rui has been working in the living room of Wuhan since February 8. With more than 400 beds in Hall B, which is run by the national team, the shelter was filled as soon as it opened. "there were so many patients that I almost died on the first day, " said Moray, who said he had planned to take only 50 patients on the first day, but more than 100 came.

After the initial consultation, Mo Rui found that many patients with a longer course of illness, to the shelter has been more than 10 days of symptoms. "There's a lot of family cluster infections, " said the report, with couples moving into the shelter at the same time. "There's even a family of three. ". Fu Xian, a volunteer in Wuhan who helps people seeking help, said family cluster infections accounted for about 30 percent of the calls he received.

And outside the Shelter Hospital, Wuhan still has a large number of suspected cases lingering outside. From the point of view of prevention and control, they may be mobile source of infection, belonging to the "four categories" of personnel. On February 6, the Central Government asked Wuhan to take the city's strength to investigate the "four categories" of personnel, not a family, not a person, will fall to the community. After screening, the community is responsible for arranging suspected cases to be quarantined at the isolation point.

Since then, Wuhan has formed a "pyramid"-like prevention and treatment system, severe treatment in the spire, treatment of mild cases in the shelter center, and suspected patients of prevention and control are handed over to the community, the latter became the "pyramid" battle array of the largest number of towers.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
As of February 13, there were 1,223 workers in the shelter of the living room in Wuhan, including 197 doctors and 839 nurses. Among them, 1,114 foreign aid workers from the province. | Hwang woo-suk

Wuhan has a resident population of 11.08 million, spread over 1,287 communities and 1,883 villages. Since January 24, Wuhan will be diverted to the community admission gate, the latter has been under no less pressure than the hospital. In more than one community, staff members resigned for fear of infection or pressure to be screened. The investigation of thousands of people, combined with the report, transfer, protection of living materials and other work, so that the community tired of running, prevention and control quality uneven. Under military orders, there are still blind spots.

A community secretary in the East L. District of Wuhan told this newspaper that he could only do his best to conduct a thorough investigation. "Some people are registered here but live elsewhere. These are empty storefronts. We don't know where they are until they come for us. We can't report it if we can't find someone. It's missing. Others turn in and leave messages at the police station, "these are the dead zones of work. In addition, the lack of professional knowledge and protective equipment of community workers also increased the difficulty of screening.

Fu told the Financial Times that as of Feb. 14, his volunteer organization had received 574 requests for help, and only 171, or 29 percent, had been hospitalized. "first there is a lack of beds, and second there is a lack of transfer vehicles, " Fu said, adding that the situation has improved since Feb. 14, when a large number of patients seeking help began to be admitted to hospital. Due to busy volunteer service, he has not yet compiled the latest statistics, saying there are still a small number of patients not admitted. "Wuhan is still a work in progress, " Zhong Nanshan told a news conference on Feb. 18

"compared with the places of import, the number of infected people in Wuhan has not been fully known, nor is there a more accurate estimate of the scale of the spread of the disease. " On February 12, Chen Yixin, deputy head of the Central Guidance Group, was in charge of the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters, the number of potential infections in Wuhan may still be relatively large. To this end, he once again stressed the issue of research beds, to ensure that "should be collected" , rather than "beds and other people" , "patients and other beds.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medical Staff of Wuhan Shelter Hospital | expedition photography

According to the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters, as of 22:00 on February 13, the number of designated hospital beds in Wuhan is 13,859, and the number of beds in Mount Vulcan and Mount Thor is 1,159, totaling 15,018. As of 4:00 PM on February 14th, there are more than 7,600 beds in 9"Shelter Hospitals" in service in Wuhan, and other shelters are opening in Foshan, at that time, the number of beds still can not meet the Wuhan more than 30,000 confirmed cases, "should be collected" road block and long.

On February 15, the central guidance team again stressed the need for the O to strengthen its capacity for admission and treatment. At the same time, a number of hospitals in Wuhan began to Transform, in a large number of additional relief medical personnel on the basis of geometry to increase bed capacity. Before February 20, Wuhan will reserve 100,000 beds, of which 14,000 are for serious cases, 30,000 are for mild cases, and 56,000 are for centralized isolation.

Last-ditch mobilization-like, a number of volunteers have said to this newspaper, "a bed hard to get" phenomenon is easing. Both Fu and another volunteer said they had received far fewer requests for help. Initially, one hundred people a day sought help; now there are only a dozen, or even single digits, a day. Many also seek transfer rather than admission. "This is unprecedented, " Fu said. Official figures also show that the number of new cases and the rate of serious illnesses have fallen after stocks were released and quarantined.

It's a three-dimensional space-time battle against disease and contagion. After layers of strategic deployment, the General Attack Command has been issued, the decisive battle is imminent. Yang Gonghuan said: "It is too early to talk about victory, nor can it be said that Wuhan has no dead ends, but at least people's hearts are more confident. "
